   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The
                           Provoked Husband</title></hi>].<note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>The Provoked Husband</title>; or, a Journey to
                              London; A Comedy, In Five Acts; By <ref
                                 target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Sir J. Vanbrugh</ref>, and <ref
                                 target="people.html#CibberColley">C. Cibber</ref>, Esq. As
                              Performed at the Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane"
                                 >Drury Lane</ref> and <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent
                                 Garden</ref>. Printed Under the Authority of the Managers From the
                              Prompt Book. With Remarks by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs"
                                 >Mrs. Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman,
                        Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row, pp. 3-6. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title level="m">The British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays,
                              Which Are Acted At the Theatres Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, and <ref
                                 target="people.html#Haymarket">Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under the
                              Authority of the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical and
                              Critical Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                 Inchbald</ref>.</title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. IX. <hi
                           rendition="#italics">
                           <title>Provoked Wife</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Provoked Husband</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Love Makes a Man</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>She Wou'd and She Wou'd Not</title></hi>. <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title>Careless Husband</title></hi>. London:
                        Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first
                        performance of this play was staged at the <ref
                           target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury Lane</ref> on January
                           10<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi> of 1728. Bernadette D. Woodburn, Laura
                        DeWitt, and Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics"
                           >The Criticism Archive</hi>. </note></title>
                  <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </bibl>
            </head>
            <p>The artist, who raised the famed structure at Blenheim, laid the foundation of this
               play. He died in the midst of his labour, and the dramatic edifice was erected by
                     another.<note><ref target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Vanbrugh</ref>, as well as
                  being an author, was an architect and designed the Blenheim Palace for <ref
                     target="people.html#MarlboroughJohnChurchill">John Churchill</ref>.
                  Then-entitled <hi rendition="#italics"><title>A Journey to London</title></hi>,
                     <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Provoked Husband</title></hi> remained
                  unfinished upon <ref target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Vanbrugh</ref>'s death in
                  1726. He left the manuscript to his friend <ref target="people.html#CibberColley"
                     >Colley Cibber</ref> to finish.</note></p>
            <p><ref target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Sir John Vanbrugh</ref>, celebrated as an
               architect, and no less so as a dramatist, was descended from an ancient family in
                     Cheshire,<note><ref target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Vanbrugh</ref> grew up in
                  Chester, the county town of the region Cheshire in Northwest England. <ref
                     target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Vanbrugh</ref>'s father, Giles Vanbrugh, was
                  a wealthy sugar refiner and the son of a Flemish immigrant.</note> and born about
               the middle of the reign of <ref target="people.html#CharlesIIKingofEngland">King
                  Charles the Second</ref>. He was a man of wit, yet a man of business; and without
               suffering any one of the many talents which he possessed to destroy the other, he
               made the most of every gift which Providence had bestowed on him, and left an example
               to poets&#8212;that affluence and the muses may dwell in the same habitation,
               provided the door is not shut against prudence and industry.</p>
            <p><ref target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Sir John</ref>, with all his wisdom and
               discretion, had still, in the decline of his life, some past deeds of which he
               repented; and that his contrition was sincere, his amendment appears to have given
               ample proof&#8212;his regret was, that he had ever written a licentious play; and he
               began to write this moral drama, "<title>The Provoked Husband</title>," in atonement
               for his former le-<lb/><fw type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw><pb n="4"
                  />vity.<note>In the Prologue to <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Provok'd
                        Husband; or, A Journey to London</title></hi> (1728), <ref
                     target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref> writes:<quote><lg type="stanza">
                        <l>This Play took Birth from Principles of Truth,</l>
                        <l>To make Amends for Errors past, of Youth,</l>
                        <l>A Bard, that's now no more, in Riper days,</l>
                        <l>Conscious review'd the License of his Plays:</l>
                        <l>And though Applause his wanton Muse had fir'd,</l>
                        <l>Himself condemn'd what sensual Minds admir'd.</l>
                        <l>At length, he own'd, that Plays should let you see</l>
                        <l>Not only, What you Are, but Ought to Be:</l>
                        <l>Though Vice was natural, 'twas never meant,</l>
                        <l>The Stage should shew it, but for Punishment!</l>
                        <l>Warm with that Thought, his Muse once more took flame,</l>
                        <l>Resolv'd to bring licentious Life to Shame.</l>
                     </lg></quote></note> Heaven, it is hoped, accepted his good intention, though
               it forbade the completion of his pious desire.</p>
            <p><ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Colley Cibber</ref>, the author, actor, and
               manager, who finished this work, which the deceased <ref
                  target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Vanbrugh</ref> had commenced, has given an
               account of the above laudable design, which was communicated to him by the author,
               some little time previous to his death; when <ref target="people.html#CibberColley"
                  >Cibber</ref> waited upon him to inquire after the progress he had made in
               composing his new comedy, which, as the manager of the theatre, he was impatient to
               have in his possession.</p>
            <p><ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref> relates, that <ref
                  target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Sir John</ref> had even carried his
               conscientious scruples so far, that he did not mean his gay, dissipated, woman of
               fashion should be pardoned at the end of the play; but that she should be repudiated
               by her husband, and all her honourable friends, as a proper warning to the unthinking
               wives of that inconsiderate period.<note>In <ref target="people.html#VanbrughJohn"
                     >Vanbrugh</ref>'s original manuscript, Lady Townly, a socialite with a lax
                  lifestyle, is ultimately turned out by her husband for her indiscretions. However,
                     <ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref> felt that this ending was
                  too harsh for a comedy and opted for the married couple to come to a resolution.
                     <ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref> describes this alteration
                  in the "To the Reader" section prefacing <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The
                        Provok'd Husband; or, A Journey to London</title></hi> (1728).</note></p>
            <p>Whether <ref target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Vanbrugh</ref> had perceived any
               symptoms of approaching dissolution when he planned this catastrophe, is not
               said&#8212;but <ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Colley Cibber</ref>, in perfect
               health and spirits when the departed author's manuscript was laid before him, felt
               more compassion for female frailty, and less zeal for the conversion of the female
               world, than to give such a severe example as the original author had intended, to the
               splendid rows of his side boxes.</p>
            <p><ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref>, to his honour, preserved <ref
                  target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Vanbrugh</ref>'s moral, yet complied with his
               own feelings and taste.&#8212;By this artful lenity, the cause of morality was,
                     perhaps,<lb/><fw><hi rendition="#indent8">4</hi></fw><pb n="5"/> more benefited
               than it would have been by more rigid means. Lady Townly, by <ref
                  target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Vanbrugh</ref>'s plot, must have been made too
               unamiable for compassion: the interest in her final punishment would then have been
               lost, and her case rendered so desperate, that none but the reprobate would have
               found a resemblance of themselves in her [<hi rendition="#italics">sic</hi>]
               character&#8212;a description of women, too hardened for the reformation of a
               dramatist.</p>
            <p><ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Colley Cibber</ref>, in his variety of
               occupations, held a post the most difficult to guard against enemies. He was the
               manager of a London theatre.<note><ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref>
                  served as an actor-manager at the <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre
                     Royal, Drury Lane</ref> from 1710 to 1732.</note> In this station, he had to
               repulse numberless unskilful adventurers, both as authors, and actors, to tell them
               in plain terms, that they were such&#8212;and they, of course, resented this want of
               supposed discernment in their favour.</p>
            <p>When "<title>The Provoked Husband</title>" first appeared, <ref
                  target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref>'s enemies, it is said, knowing that
               part of the work was his, and part the renowned <ref
                  target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Vanbrugh</ref>'s, they resolved to spare the
               dead man, but to have no mercy on the living one. In this design they were happily
               disappointed; for, mistaking the Wronghead family<note>The Wrongheads are an
                  archetypal country-bumpkin clan who journey to London for the first time in the
                  play's subplot. The family acts inappropriately at every turn, putting themselves
                  in constant peril.</note> as the production of <ref
                  target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref>'s pen, and the house of Lord Townly
               as proceeding from <ref target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Sir John</ref>'s, they
               applauded the very scenes they came to condemn, and condemned those which they came
               to applaud.</p>
            <p><ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref> took the honest revenge of
               pointing out to them their error, by publishing the manuscript of <ref
                  target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Sir John</ref> exactly as he left it; where all
               the merit of the elegant part of the drama was seen to be wanting; and that it was
                  <ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref>, and not <ref
                  target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Vanbrugh</ref>, to whom they<lb/><fw type="sig"
                     ><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 3</hi></fw><pb n="6"/> had been indebted for the
               chief part of the dialogue between Lord and Lady Townly; more especially for that
               admirable scene at the conclusion of the comedy.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref> included <ref
                     target="people.html#VanbrughJohn">Vanbrugh</ref>'s original manuscript in his
                  1728 publication of the play. <ref target="people.html#CibberColley">Cibber</ref>
                  justified the publication of <ref target="people.html#VanbrughJohn"
                  >Vanbrugh</ref>'s pages in the "To the Reader" section prefacing <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Provok'd Husband; or, A Journey to
                        London</title></hi> (1728): "I had no other way of taking those many Faults
                  to my self, which may be justly found in my presuming to finish it." The scene to
                  which <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> refers is Act V, scene
                  ii, in which Lord and Lady Townly are reconciled and she realizes that "married
                  happiness is never found from home."</note></p>
            <p>Although refined characters are sometimes so dull on the stage, and those of low
               humour so pleasant, that elegance gives place to nature unadorned&#8212;in this
               comedy it is otherwise; for here, that which is elegant is interesting, and all which
               is vulgar is tedious and insipid, with the exception of Sir Francis,<note>Sir Francis
                  Wronghead is the father and leader of the Wronghead clan.</note> who is a
               character drawn with truth and judgment, though somewhat removed in worldly
               comprehension from the country gentleman of the present day; and as such, not
               perfectly understood by the majority of an audience.</p>
         </div>
